No chin strap, no dark on vent or inner thighs visible when it rolled over. White on flanks visible when resting, extending higher up posteriorly. Bill slightly thicker than PALO, bill intermediate in blockiness between PALO and COLO, etc, etc. Very well documented individual

Peltodoris nobilis was located on reef at a depth of 40 feet. Lengths were not measured. Water temperature was 54 degrees F.

Note the large feeding scar on the unidentified sponge. This indicates that P. nobilis feeds on this sponge. The color difference between the large yellow individual and the smaller orange individuals may indicate that the smaller animals were previously feeding on the sponge Acarnus erithacus, another food source that was located nearby.

Lots of these cigar-shaped egg masses were stranded on the beach at Gaviota. This one was 120 mm long and up to 13.5 mm in diameter.

description: I observed this turtle in a pond in the Carmel Valley area which was also occupied by what appeared to be several slider turtles. The Southern painted turtle is not native to the area, so like the sliders, it must have been a pet which escaped or was turned loose.

One of the more interesting interactions I observed from 5 years spent studying river otters was this half-assed attempt at hunting snowy egret. 

I had seen otters take birds only twice prior to this. Otters go under the water and pull the birds down and drown them. The marsh otters I saw do this were stealthy and secretive in there approach. This otter and the other actual river living otters never took birds that I saw in direct observation or in scat examination but every once in awhile they would take a run at an egret or heron. 

This otter appeared to think a quick change of direction and lunge would work but the snowy egret easily got away. I found it interesting that the bird flew a few feet away, next to the much larger Great Egret and seemed to be using the larger bird as a deterrent. The otter swam off to hunt crayfish and the egrets went back to stalking their own prey.

This photo was taken in a small park within Griffith Park in Southern California. After being caught and slammed into the ground several times, the gopher was no longer with us and was swallowed, whole. I was able to see the gopher sliding down the Egret's throat. The Egret had to shake it's head and gesticulate often in order to get it to finally slide all of the way down it's gullet and finally into the crop for digestion.

The Grainyhand Hermit Crab is recognizable by the many blue spots covering its legs and claws. This one is wearing the algae-covered shell of a turban snail.

This individual was separated from the similar Bluebanded Hermit Crab (P. samuelis) by its greenish and yellow antennae. The Bluebanded Hermit Crab has red antennae. 

The Hairy Hermit Crab is also more inclined to use Olive shells while the Bluebanded is more often found in turban shells. This one is using a Purple Olive (Callianax biplicata) shell.

This species of anemone is native to Asia but has been introduced widely around the  world from ballast water and off the holds of ships. It is extremely tolerant to a wide range of abiotic conditions (salinity, temperature...), a condition that has certainly aided its spread. These individuals were found in the shallow water at the north end of the South Marsh where it abuts Whistelstop Lagoon.

It previously went by the name  Haliplanella luciae.

description: UC Davis Arboretum, Davis, CA

This Great Egret is eating a Botta's Pocket Gopher (Thomomys bottae). This photo was taken in a small park within Griffith Park in Southern California. When I first saw it, it was standing motionless, and did so for about 8-10 minutes. I didn't notice it at first because it was so still, and when I did finally notice it, I thought it was some kind of bird statue... until I saw it suddenly move and spear something in the grass with it's bill. Suddenly, it had a meal of this gopher. It was fascinating to watch. The three photos show, first, the Great Egret picking up the gopher, which it then proceeded to slam down into the ground several times. (I suppose to kill it.) Then it began to swallow it whole (the second photo). And finally, I observed the gopher sliding down the Egret's throat. The Egret had to shake it's head and gesticulate often in order to get it to finally slide all of the way down it's gullet and finally into the crop for digestion. There's a video of this Great Egret eating the Botta's Pocket Gopher on my YouTube account at https://youtu.be/NJMr1MsFMQU.

It was eating what appeared to be a coot, based on the leg/foot structure (all that was left). The hawk had a rufous tail and rufous leggings, which were quite striking in the field.  I've been told by a few Bay Area birders that it's a dark intermediate (dark rufous) morph.

This coho carcass was discovered in lower Lagunitas Creek after spawning by the MMWD biologist team, who work collaboratively with SPAWN. The photo shows the removal of the inner ear bone, or otolith, to be preserved and incorporated into an ongoing research project based out of UC Berkeley using otolith micro-chemistry to determine the home watershed of individual spawning coho salmon.
The coho spawned at two locations along lower Lagunitas Creek outside of the SPAWN office. This large adult swam upstream from the redd for a moment, into focus for this shot.

This female coho was holding on her redd defending it from other salmonids for over a week in the exact same location along upper Lagunitas Creek, upstream of the Leo Cronin Viewing Area parking lot. A great attraction on the SPAWN Creekwalks!

description: Found another today! This chilly, wet and rainy morning ~ 9am, I was on NE side of house placing an elbow attachment onto a roof downspout. I had to remove a piece of slate that was under the spout (deflects storm-water away from house) in order to fit the elbow. I had a feeling that somebody was under there because my yard is home to several spp. of salamanders, so I carefully lifted it up and Good Earth, I found another arboreal salamander approx. 9 cm (3.6") long! On the NE side of the house are densely planted Pteridophyte spp., a 3 m (~9') tall Camellia spp., a clump of prostrate growing Rosemarinus spp., and Oxalis spp. makes up the bulk of ground cover. A dark "Scots mulch" type of bark, and slabs of slate are some other features. These salamanders are inspiring me to plant some oak this spring!

description: While driving along Hicks Valley Rd in Marin County (accessed from Pt Reyes-Petaluma Rd), I noticed something swimming in a farm pond on the north side of the road.  I thought it might be a river otter, so my husband and I stopped to check it out.  Upon getting a better look, we determined that it clearly wasn't a river otter (I just saw one of those yesterday at Healdsburg Ridge Open Space Preserve).  Rather, it had the look of a small beaver.  We watched it swim around for a while - it looked like a long rectangular block with a long, thin tail.  Once, out of the corner of my eye, I saw it flip its tail through the air.  As far as I could tell, it was nothing more than a skinny, round tail (i.e. not a beaver tail).  According to California Wildlife Habitat Relationships range maps, muskrats occur in this area but beavers don't.  Since nutrias have been eradicated from California, it seems that Common Muskrat is the only reasonable identification; and what we saw matches pictures of muskrats that I've found online.  As we were leaving, a second individual appeared.  It was nearing sunset.  I got a crummy picture of one of the individuals - perhaps the body shape will aid in confirming the species id.
